Test Plan

Project: Windows Vulnerability & Hardening Auditor
Role: Validation & Case Study Team
Application Type: Defensive Security Assessment Tool
Technology Stack:

C++ (Application logic & UI)

Python (Security scanner & rules engine)

PowerShell (Read-only system interrogation)

HTML/CSS (Report generation)

SQLite (Optional scan history storage)



1. Purpose of the Test Plan

  The purpose of this test plan is to define the strategy, scope, and methodology used to validate the correctness, reliability, and safety of the Windows Vulnerability & Hardening Auditor.

  This test plan ensures that:

  Security misconfigurations are detected accurately

  Severity levels are assigned consistently

  Integration between C++ and Python functions correctly

  The system handles permission limitations gracefully

  Reports are accurate, readable, and actionable

  The tool operates ethically and non-invasively

2. Test Scope
  2.1 In-Scope Testing

    Local Windows system scanning

    Read-only interrogation of system security settings

    C++ execution of Python scanner

    JSON-based result exchange

    UI display and filtering of findings

    HTML report generation

    Error handling and permission awareness

  2.2 Out-of-Scope Testing

    Vulnerability exploitation

    Password cracking or brute-force attacks

    Network scanning of external systems

    Malware simulation

    Any modification of system settings

3. Test Environment

  Operating System: Windows 10 / Windows 11

  Execution Context:

  Administrator account

  Standard (non-admin) user account

  Tools:

    PowerShell (read-only commands)

    Python runtime

    C++ compiled application

  Test Data:

    Live system configuration

    Controlled misconfiguration scenarios (where permitted)

4. Test Strategy

  Testing will be conducted using functional, integration, and negative testing approaches.

  4.1 Functional Testing

    Validates correct detection of security configurations and vulnerabilities.

  4.2 Integration Testing

    Validates communication and data handling between:

    C++ application

    Python scanner

    PowerShell commands

  4.3 Negative & Reliability Testing

    Validates system behavior when:

    Permissions are insufficient

    Python execution fails

    JSON output is malformed or incomplete

5. Severity Validation Criteria

Severity validation ensures findings are classified consistently and defensibly.

Finding	Expected Severity
Antivirus / Defender disabled	Critical
Firewall disabled	Critical
SMBv1 enabled	High
BitLocker disabled	High
Guest account enabled	High
Remote Desktop enabled	Medium
User Account Control disabled	Medium
Informational system details	Low

Severity validation confirms that scanner-assigned severity matches this matrix.

6. Test Case Summary

  A total of 10–15 test cases will be executed, covering the following categories:

  6.1 Security Feature Detection Tests

    Antivirus / Defender status

    Firewall profiles (Domain, Private, Public)

    SMBv1 enablement

    BitLocker encryption status

    Remote Desktop configuration

    UAC status

    Guest account status

    Local administrator group membership

  6.2 Integration & Reliability Tests

    C++ initiates Python scanner successfully

    JSON results parsed correctly by C++

    Graceful handling of Python execution failure

    Graceful handling of empty or malformed JSON

    Scan execution without administrator privileges

    Handling of PowerShell permission errors without crashing

7. Test Case Template

  Each test case follows this standardized format:

  Test Case ID

  Description

  Preconditions

  Test Steps

  Expected Results

  Pass / Fail

  Notes

  This ensures repeatability and clear documentation for final reporting.

8. Scan Result Validation Template

  Each executed scan will be documented using a standardized template containing:

  System scenario description

  Scan timestamp

  Detected vulnerabilities

  Severity count summary

  C++ UI behavior (tables, filters, summaries)

  Errors or warnings

  HTML report accuracy and completeness

9. Entry & Exit Criteria
  9.1 Entry Criteria

    C++ application can execute Python scanner

    Python scanner produces JSON output

    UI is capable of displaying scan results

  9.2 Exit Criteria

    All planned test cases executed

    Test results documented

    Case study outputs captured

    No critical failures preventing scan completion

10. Test Deliverables

  Finalized test case document

  Severity validation reference

  Scan validation templates

  Executed case study documentation

  Test results summary

  Case Studies for Class Discussion & Validation

  These case studies are not hypothetical fluff — each one exists to prove the program runs correctly under real conditions.



Case Study 1: Secure System Baseline
Scenario Description
A Windows system configured with strong security controls enabled.
System Conditions
Antivirus enabled and up to date
Firewall enabled on all profiles
BitLocker enabled
SMBv1 disabled
UAC enabled
Guest account disabled
RDP disabled

Expected Results
Few or no high/critical findings
Mostly Low or Informational entries
Accurate severity counts
Clean HTML report generation

Validation Purpose
Confirms no false positives
Demonstrates accuracy on well-hardened systems
Builds trust in tool reliability


